                     </persName>
                  
               
                  </rs>. The Evidence declared that the Prisoner came into her Brother's House, and sat down with three more and drank a Shilling, and he paid a false Shilling; then he called for a Pennyworth of Tobacco, and gave her another, and had a 11 d. in Farthings again; then he called for a pint of Drink, and a Pennyworth of Brandy, and gave her a Sixpence, and he had 4 d. in Farthings, after that he sat down, and spent the rest of the Money; and it happened that a Nieghbour being by, mistrusted him, and lookt upon the Money, and found 6 s. and 6 d. of Naughty Money which he had taken. The Prisoner denied the Fact, and alledged that he paid good Money, but it was proved to the contrary; the Jury found him <rs id="t16970224-33-verdict186" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t16970224-33-verdict186" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               guilty
            </rs> of the said Misdemeanor.</p>
